│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion failure in isSingleSourceMaskImpl when   │
│ vector-combine asks TTI to classify a shuffle mask. The mask contains         │
│ elements 4 and 7, but the helper is called with NumOpElts = 2 (the result     │
│ vector length), causing the bounds check to assert because 4 and 7 are not    │
│ less than 2*NumOpElts (which is 4).                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The pass visits the selects and the shuffle, and then aborts while querying   │
│ shuffle properties via TTI. The first transformation point is the analysis in │
│ Instructions.cpp::isSingleSourceMaskImpl, invoked by                          │
│ ShuffleVectorInst::isSelectMask through                                       │
│ BasicTTIImpl::improveShuffleKindFromMask. The mask is <4,7> and Ty appears to │
│ be the result type (<2 x float>), so NumSrcElts is computed as 2 in           │
│ BasicTTIImpl.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ BasicTTIImpl::improveShuffleKindFromMask uses                                 │
│ Ty->getElementCount().getKnownMinValue() as NumSrcElts for all helper         │
│ predicates (isSelectMask, isReverseMask, etc.). Those predicates assume       │
│ NumSrcElts is the per-operand element count, but in TTI getShuffleCost the    │
│ only type available is often the result type. For two-source shuffles that    │
│ shrink the result (like extracting lanes), mask elements can legitimately     │
│ reference indices up to 2 * operand elements - 1, which may exceed 2 * result │
│ elements - 1. Passing the result element count into isSingleSourceMaskImpl    │
│ leads to the assert. Since calling contexts may not know the true operand     │
│ element count, the predicates should not assert on out-of-bounds indices;     │
│ they should conservatively return false.                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the assertion in isSingleSourceMaskImpl is too strong for general  │
│ mask classification utilities used by TTI with limited operand size           │
│ information. A robust fix is to replace the assert with a defensive check     │
│ that returns false when indices are out of the assumed bounds.                │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/IR/Instructions.cpp                                          │
│ - Lines: 1904-1912                                                            │
│ - Change: Replace the assertion on out-of-bounds mask elements with a         │
│ conditional that returns false when encountering any element outside [0,      │
│ NumOpElts*2), while still allowing -1 (undef). This prevents crashing when    │
│ TTI passes the result vector width as NumOpElts.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested code change:                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ for (int I : Mask) {                                                          │
│   if (I == -1)                                                                │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│   // If the caller provided a NumOpElts that is smaller than the operand      │
│   // vector length, mask indices may appear out-of-bounds. In that case,      │
│   // conservatively report that this is not a single-source mask.             │
│   if (I < 0 || I >= (NumOpElts * 2))                                          │
│     return false;                                                             │
│   UsesLHS |= (I < NumOpElts);                                                 │
│   UsesRHS |= (I >= NumOpElts);                                                │
│   if (UsesLHS && UsesRHS)                                                     │
│     return false;                                                             │
│ }                                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ This replaces the assert with an early return false.                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By making isSingleSourceMaskImpl robust against out-of-bounds mask elements   │
│ when the caller does not have accurate operand vector sizes, we avoid the     │
│ crash and let TTI classification fall back (returning false) instead of       │
│ aborting. This preserves the invariant that assertions model internal         │
│ correctness assumptions, while acknowledging that external TTI queries may    │
│ not satisfy those assumptions and should be handled gracefully.               │
